Note:
BF #381 regression test: allocator hygiene. Stress-tests the owned-heap
allocator at compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa for:

  1. Repeated allocate / deallocate cycles with varying sizes do not
     corrupt heap metadata. A corrupted chunk header would manifest as
     a glibc-style "munmap_chunk(): invalid pointer" warning at the
     next deallocation OR at process exit.

  2. Out-of-memory behavior: when the kernel rejects mmap (typically
     because the address-space request is unreasonable), allocate
     returns 0 cleanly without crashing or emitting diagnostic noise.

  3. Pointer ownership boundary: deallocate is a no-op on pointers
     outside the allocator's bounding box (slab registry + owned_addr
     range), so passing a stack address, an argv-derived pointer, or
     a foreign-library pointer is safe and returns 0.

  4. Size-class fast path coverage: many allocations of small sizes
     exercise the pool slab fast path; large allocations exercise the
     mmap arm. Both must round-trip the size correctly so deallocate
     returns memory to the right tier.

The 1000-iteration stress loop is deterministic (uses a linear
congruential generator seeded with a fixed value) so failures
reproduce identically across runs.

Reporting follows the canonical tests/test_utils.runa convention:
each case is an assert against the expected outcome, the suite prints
"ALL TESTS PASSED" and exits 0 when every case holds, and exits with
the failure count otherwise. The stress loop reports a single status
code (0 = clean; 402 = allocate failed mid-stress; 407 = allocation
contents corrupted) identifying the first failure class, matching the
original exit-code legend for this file.
:End Note

Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as T
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Heap
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be T.create_test_results()
    T.begin_suite(results, "runtime.allocator_hygiene")

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: Case 1: basic allocate / deallocate round-trip with a
    Note: small (cache-line-sized) buffer. Establishes that the
    Note: allocator is alive and self-consistent.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let p1 be proc allocate from Heap with 64
    T.assert_not_null(results, "Case 1: first allocation succeeds", p1)

    Note: 8-byte alignment is a hard invariant: pool slabs hand out
    Note: cells aligned to their size-class (>=8 for size 64), and
    Note: brk/mmap arms round up to 16-byte alignment for SSE
    Note: compatibility.
    Let p1_low_bits be p1 modulo by 8
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 1: pointer 8-byte aligned", p1_low_bits, 0)

    Let _dealloc_r1 be proc deallocate from Heap with p1
    Note: deallocate's return value is informational (1 == path taken,
    Note: 0 == pointer ignored). We do not gate on its value here -
    Note: what matters is that the call does not abort.

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: Case 2: deterministic stress loop, 1000 iterations across
    Note: pool slab classes (8 to 256 bytes) and the mmap arm
    Note: (>= 4096 bytes). The LCG below is the classic Numerical
    Note: Recipes constants - period 2^32, uniform enough for stress
    Note: rotation. Seeded with 0x9E3779B9 (the golden-ratio fractional
    Note: bits) so the size sequence is reproducible.
    Note: stress_status: 0 = clean, 402 = allocate failed mid-stress,
    Note: 407 = allocation contents corrupted (first failure recorded,
    Note: loop exits early so the failing iteration is deterministic).
    Note: ============================================================
    Let lcg_state be 2654435769  Note: 0x9E3779B9
    Let lcg_a be 1664525
    Let lcg_c be 1013904223
    Let lcg_mod be 4294967296  Note: 2^32

    Let stress_status be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 1000:
        Note: Step the LCG. Modulo by 2^32 to keep within 32-bit
        Note: range so the product does not overflow into the sign
        Note: bit on the next iteration.
        Set lcg_state to ((lcg_state multiplied by lcg_a) plus lcg_c) modulo by lcg_mod

        Note: Map to a size class. Bucket 0..3 -> 16 bytes, 4..7 -> 64,
        Note: 8..11 -> 256, 12..14 -> 1024, 15 -> 65536 (mmap arm).
        Note: Distribution: 25% / 25% / 25% / 18.75% / 6.25% of small
        Note: allocations + occasional large.
        Let bucket be (lcg_state divided by 268435456) modulo by 16  Note: top nibble of 32-bit state
        Let alloc_size be 16
        If bucket is greater than or equal to 4:
            Set alloc_size to 64
        End If
        If bucket is greater than or equal to 8:
            Set alloc_size to 256
        End If
        If bucket is greater than or equal to 12:
            Set alloc_size to 1024
        End If
        If bucket is equal to 15:
            Set alloc_size to 65536
        End If

        Let stress_ptr be proc allocate from Heap with alloc_size
        If stress_ptr is equal to 0:
            Set stress_status to 402
            Set i to 1000
        Otherwise:
            Note: Touch the first and last bytes of the allocation to
            Note: catch any latent bounds-check failure. The byte writes
            Note: also serve as the canary roundtrip for free-list
            Note: integrity across the deallocate that follows.
            Let _w1 be proc memory_set_byte from Memory with stress_ptr, 0, 170  Note: 0xAA
            Let _w2 be proc memory_set_byte from Memory with stress_ptr, alloc_size minus 1, 187  Note: 0xBB

            Let read_first be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with stress_ptr, 0
            Let read_last be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with stress_ptr, alloc_size minus 1
            If read_first is not equal to 170:
                Set stress_status to 407
                Set i to 1000
            End If
            If read_last is not equal to 187:
                Set stress_status to 407
                Set i to 1000
            End If

            Let _free be proc deallocate from Heap with stress_ptr

            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
    End While
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 2: 1000-iteration stress loop clean", stress_status, 0)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: Case 3: deallocate(0) MUST be a safe no-op. This is the
    Note: documented NULL-guard contract and is relied upon by every
    Note: caller in the codebase that does not pre-check.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let dealloc_null_r be proc deallocate from Heap with 0
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 3: deallocate(NULL) returns 0", dealloc_null_r, 0)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: Case 4: deallocate on a pointer OUTSIDE the allocator's
    Note: bounding box must be a safe no-op. The owned_addr_min /
    Note: owned_addr_max pre-filter (lines 3508-3513 of layout.runa)
    Note: catches stack addresses, argv pointers, and any foreign
    Note: pointer numerically below or above the brk/mmap region.
    Note: We pass a small positive integer (8) which is guaranteed
    Note: to be below any plausible mmap/brk region (the kernel
    Note: reserves the entire first page 0..4095 as the NULL guard,
    Note: and brk/mmap regions live far above that). The
    Note: ptr < owned_addr_min check fires and returns 0 cleanly.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let dealloc_off_r be proc deallocate from Heap with 8
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 4: deallocate(off-heap) returns 0", dealloc_off_r, 0)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: Case 5: large-allocation OOM path. We request a positive
    Note: but unreasonably large allocation (1 TiB) which the kernel
    Note: will reject. The allocator's mmap arm checks the syscall
    Note: return value and returns 0 cleanly when mmap fails.
    Note: A successful allocation here would mean the kernel actually
    Note: reserved 1 TiB of address space - the test still passes in
    Note: that case (we immediately free) but the OOM-handling code
    Note: path went unexercised on this run. Either path is a pass:
    Note: reaching the record_pass call at all proves the allocate
    Note: call neither crashed nor aborted.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let oom_size be 1099511627776  Note: 1 TiB
    Let oom_ptr be proc allocate from Heap with oom_size
    If oom_ptr is not equal to 0:
        Let _oom_free be proc deallocate from Heap with oom_ptr
        Note: Successful: kernel granted 1 TiB. Allocator returned
        Note: a valid pointer; we freed it cleanly. No assertion
        Note: failure - OOM path simply was not triggered.
    End If
    T.record_pass(results, "Case 5: 1 TiB allocate handled without crash")

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: Case 6: allocate-write-allocate-write pattern to catch
    Note: free-list corruption. Two consecutive small allocations
    Note: from the same size class typically come from adjacent
    Note: free-list slots in the same pool slab. If a deallocate
    Note: somehow corrupts the embedded next-pointer of the freed
    Note: slot, the next allocate will hand out a garbage pointer.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let p_a be proc allocate from Heap with 64
    T.assert_not_null(results, "Case 6: allocation A succeeds", p_a)
    Let _w_a be proc memory_set_byte from Memory with p_a, 0, 161  Note: 0xA1

    Let p_b be proc allocate from Heap with 64
    T.assert_not_null(results, "Case 6: allocation B succeeds", p_b)
    Let _w_b be proc memory_set_byte from Memory with p_b, 0, 162  Note: 0xA2

    T.assert_not_equal(results, "Case 6: A and B are distinct live pointers", p_a, p_b)

    Let r_a be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with p_a, 0
    Let r_b be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with p_b, 0
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 6: A contents intact", r_a, 161)
    T.assert_equal(results, "Case 6: B contents intact", r_b, 162)

    Let _fa be proc deallocate from Heap with p_a
    Let _fb be proc deallocate from Heap with p_b

    T.print_summary(results)
    Let exit_code be T.get_failed(results)
    T.destroy_test_results(results)
    Return exit_code
End Process
